article.headline: Bucks' 7-0 run puts it away
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- With the exception of a two-minute stretch late in the fourth quarter, the Milwaukee Bucks pretty much had their way against the New Jersey Nets. Tim Thomas scored 16 of his 21 points in the first quarter and Milwaukee scored eight of the final 11 points in a 92-87 victory Saturday night. After leading by 12 with 5:17 left, Milwaukee trailed 84-83 with 2:55 remaining. But the Bucks used a 7-0 run to put away New Jersey. "Those last three minutes, being able to pull the game out, that was a great game," Thomas said. "They've gone to the Finals twice," Milwaukee coach Terry Porter said of the Nets. "We got a bit tentative and passed it around too much and got out of sync offensively." Michael Redd added 17 points, including 10 in the fourth quarter, and nine rebounds for Milwaukee. Kerry Kittles had 20 points for New Jersey, which had won six of its last seven. Jason Kidd added 18 points and 10 assists, but missed 13 of his first 15 shots. "We understand that this is the type of effort we need to get a win," New Jersey coach Byron Scott said. "It's a long season. We had a little slump, but guys believe in each other on this team." Redd's two free throws gave Milwaukee a 90-84 lead with 29.5 seconds left. Kidd answered with a 3-pointer -- New Jersey's only points in the final 2:55 -- to cut the deficit to 90-87 with 21.9 remaining. "We just couldn't make plays down the stretch when we needed them," said Kenyon Martin, who had 14 points and 13 rebounds but shot 5-of-19 from the field. "We never quit though." Damon Jones made a free throw for a 91-87 lead with 20.8 left and then Kidd missed two 3-pointers in a row before Redd added another free throw. "New Jersey made its run, we made a run, Jason Kidd made his run. It was just a game of runs," said Jones, who made five of his six 3-point shots. "Fortunately for us, we were able to make plays down the stretch." New Jersey's late struggles from the field summed up its night. The Nets missed 16 of their first 18 shots and shot 32-of-83 overall. Milwaukee had an 83-71 lead after Jones' third straight 3-pointer with 5:17 remaining. But New Jersey used a 13-0 run to make things interesting. Kidd scored the final five points of the run, capped by a 3-pointer that gave New Jersey an 84-83 lead with 2:55 remaining. It was the Nets' first lead since going up 7-6.

Game notes
New Jersey's Lucious Harris didn't play after spraining his ankle Friday against Washington. Teammate Jason Collins played nine minutes of the first quarter but sat out the rest of the game with a bruised right knee. ... Milwaukee's Toni Kukoc was activated from the injured list earlier in the day after missing the last nine games with back spasms. Dan Langhi was placed on the injured list with left ankle pain. ... Milwaukee had a 16-0 run that lasted 6:56 in the first quarter. ... Each team attempted just two free throws in the first half. ... Milwaukee improved to 6-0 when holding an opponent to 89 points or less.
